        "id": "s120",
        "title": "Sports Quota",
        "persona": "student",
        "category": "Academic & Campus",
        "desc": "Claiming reserved seats under state policy.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "title": "STATUTORY QUOTA ELIGIBILITY",
                "logic": "You must first verify your eligibility under the specific State Sports Policy. Under the current rules, seats are reserved for athletes who have represented the state or nation in recognized tournaments. If the college denies your certificate, you can challenge it via a 'Representation' to the Director of Sports or the University Sports Council.",
                "objective": "Verifying legal standing for reservation",
                "checklist": [
                    "Verify certificate authenticity",
                    "Check State Sports Policy PDF",
                    "Obtain 'Rank Certificate' from Sports Dept"
                ],
                "docs": [
                    "Sports Merit Certificate",
                    "State Eligibility Letter"
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "ESCALATION TO SPORTS DIRECTORATE",
                "logic": "If the admission cell ignores your quota rank, you must file a formal grievance with the Directorate of Sports and Youth Services. They are the statutory authority for validating sports credentials. You can also file an RTI to see the 'Sports Merit List' to ensure transparency and prevent illegal seat allotments to non-deserving candidates.",
                "objective": "Enforcing merit-based admission",
                "checklist": [
                    "File grievance with Sports Director",
                    "Lodge RTI for Merit List",
                    "Request Stay on admission if rank skipped"
                ],
                "docs": [
                    "Grievance Letter",
                    "RTI Application"
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "WRIT PETITION (MANDAMUS)",
                "logic": "If all administrative remedies fail, you can approach the High Court under Article 226 for a Writ of Mandamus. The court can direct the university to follow its own published quota rules and secure your admission if your rank was unfairly bypassed. This is a common statutory remedy in educational reservation disputes.",
                "objective": "Judicial enforcement of reservation rights",
                "checklist": [
                    "Consult High Court Lawyer",
                    "Collect evidence of rank jump",
                    "File Writ for seat allocation"
                ],
                "docs": [
                    "Writ Petition (Draft)",
                    "Court Affidavit"
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "id": "s121",
        "title": "Mark Sheet Correction",
        "persona": "student",
        "category": "Academic & Campus",
        "desc": "Correction of academic marks, re-evaluation, and result tabulation errors.",
        "steps": [
            {
                "title": "CLERICAL & TABULATION AUDIT",
                "logic": "If you suspect a marking error, your first step is to request a 'Tabulation Check'. This is a statutory right to ensure that the marks on your answer sheet match those on your mark sheet. You can file a formal application for 'Scrutiny' with the University Registrar or COE (Controller of Examinations). Universities are legally bound to correct any clerical transposition errors immediately without charging a full re-evaluation fee.",
                "objective": "Verifying clerical accuracy of results",
                "checklist": [
                    "Collect copy of results/marksheet",
                    "Identify specific subject discrepancy",
                    "Lodge 'Scrutiny' application with COE"
                ],
                "docs": [
                    "Scrutiny Request Form",
                    "Current Copy of Marksheet"
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "FORMAL RE-EVALUATION REQUEST",
                "logic": "If the clerical check is correct but you believe the marking was unfair, you must apply for 'Re-evaluation'. This is governed by the specific University Ordinance. Most universities allow this within 15-21 days of result declaration. If the marks change significantly (usually >5%), the higher marks must be updated on the original degree record. Citations: UGC Guidelines on Evaluation Reforms.",
                "objective": "Securing qualitative re-assessment",
                "checklist": [
                    "Check Re-evaluation deadline",
                    "Pay prescribed re-valuation fee",
                    "Track application via University Portal"
                ],
                "docs": [
                    "Re-evaluation Application",
                    "Fee Receipt"
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "RTI FOR ANSWER SCRIPTS",
                "logic": "If the university refuses re-evaluation or transparency, you have the fundamental right to see/inspect your evaluated answer scripts under the RTI Act 2005. As per the Supreme Court in CBSE vs Aditya Bandopadhyay (2011), answer scripts are 'Information'. You can file an RTI with the PIO of the University to receive a certified copy of your script, which can then be used to challenge arbitrary marking in the High Court via a Writ Petition.",
                "objective": "Enforcing transparency and judicial review",
                "checklist": [
                    "File RTI with University PIO",
                    "Request 'Inspection' or 'Certified Copy'",
                    "Verify marking based on official 'Model Answer'"
                ],
                "docs": [
                    "RTI Application for Answer Script"
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
